The Deepest Mystery and Sweetest Comfort: Why the Doctrine of God's Decree Is the Believer's Anchor

(1689 Baptist Confession, Chapter 3 – With Complete Footnotes)

Introduction: The Doctrine That Humbles and Comforts

Chapter 3 of the 1689 Baptist Confession of Faith, entitled "Of God's Decree," stands as perhaps the most contested—yet most pastorally necessary—chapter in the entire document.¹ It addresses the eternal plan of God, the blueprint of all that comes to pass. Following the confession's logical order (Chapter 1: the principle of knowing; Chapter 2: the principle of being), Chapter 3 moves to the works of God, beginning with the internal, eternal decree before treating creation and providence in subsequent chapters.²

The chapter's seven paragraphs unfold like a theological symphony, moving from the general decree (paragraphs 1–2) to the specific decree of election and reprobation (paragraphs 3–7), all while carefully guarding biblical truth against fatalism, determinism, and human pride.³ As the Puritan theologian John Owen wrote, "The doctrine of predestination is the marrow of the gospel, not a bone of contention."⁴

Part 1: Exegetical Foundations – The Biblical Shape of God's Eternal Purpose

Chapter 3 is a masterful digest of Scripture's teaching on divine sovereignty and human responsibility. The confession's compilers—Particular Baptist elders meeting in London in 1677–1689—anchored each assertion in an array of biblical texts, refusing to speculate beyond what is written.⁵

Paragraph 1 – The General Decree: "All Things Whatsoever Comes to Pass"

The confession opens with a declaration of breathtaking scope: "God hath decreed in himself, from all eternity, by the most wise and holy counsel of his own will, freely and unchangeably, all things, whatsoever comes to pass."⁶ This language echoes the apostle Paul's affirmation in Ephesians 1:11, where he writes that God "works all things according to the counsel of his will."⁷

The confession adds four crucial modifiers to prevent misunderstanding:⁸

"In himself": The decree is internal to God, not dependent on any external condition.⁹
"From all eternity": The decree is eternal, not a response to events in time.¹⁰
"Freely": The decree flows from God's own good pleasure, not from any compulsion.¹¹
"Unchangeably": The decree is immutable; God does not alter His plan (Numbers 23:19).¹²
Yet the confession immediately qualifies this absolute statement with three safeguarding clauses:

First Safeguard: God Is Not the Author of Sin
"Yet so as thereby is God neither the author of sin nor hath fellowship with any therein."¹³ This clause addresses the most pressing objection to divine sovereignty: if God decrees all things, including sin, is He not the author of evil? The confession answers with an emphatic negative, citing James 1:13 ("Let no one say when he is tempted, 'I am being tempted by God'") and 1 John 1:5 ("God is light, and in him is no darkness at all").¹⁴

As Sam Waldron explains, "The Bible makes clear that God's motives in decreeing sin are entirely different than those of the creatures who commit or author sin. He decrees sin to happen for His own glory. They commit it to deny His glory."¹⁵ The classic illustration is Joseph's brothers: "You meant evil against me, but God meant it for good" (Genesis 50:20).¹⁶ God decreed the same act for a holy purpose; the brothers performed it for an evil purpose. The cross provides the ultimate example: "there were gathered together against your holy servant Jesus... to do whatever your hand and your plan had predestined to take place" (Acts 4:27-28).¹⁷

Second Safeguard: Violence Is Not Offered to the Creature's Will
"Nor is violence offered to the will of the creature."¹⁸ The confession insists that God's decree does not coerce human choices. Creatures act according to their nature, desires, and circumstances—all of which are within God's decree, yet without external force. The confession defines free will not as the ability to act contrary to God's decree (which would make God contingent upon the creature), but as "the ability to will whatever one wants and act on that will to accomplish that want without external constraints."¹⁹ When Judas betrayed Christ, he did so willingly, not because God forced him against his inclination.²⁰

Third Safeguard: Liberty and Contingency of Second Causes Are Established
"Nor yet is the liberty or contingency of second causes taken away, but rather established."²¹ God's sovereign decree does not render human choices meaningless or the laws of nature irrelevant. Instead, it establishes them. The confession cites Acts 4:27-28 (the predestined crucifixion) and John 19:11 (Pilate's authority given from above) to demonstrate that God's decree operates through, not against, secondary causation.²² God ordains the end and also ordains the means by which that end comes to pass.²³ This is not fatalism (where means are irrelevant) but biblical compatibilism.²⁴

The Conclusion of Paragraph 1
"in which appears his wisdom in disposing all things, and power and faithfulness in accomplishing his decree."²⁵ The doctrine of the decree is not a speculative puzzle to be solved but a doxological reality to be worshipped. It displays God's wisdom (how He orchestrates countless events toward a single glorious end), His power (nothing can thwart His plan), and His faithfulness (He keeps every promise).²⁶

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 1: Isaiah 46:10; Ephesians 1:11; Hebrews 6:17; Romans 9:15, 18; James 1:13; 1 John 1:5; Acts 4:27-28; John 19:11; Numbers 23:19.²⁷

