Paragraph 2 – The Basis of the Decree: Not Foreseen Conditions

Having established what God decrees, the confession now addresses how He decrees it. Paragraph 2 states: "Although God knoweth whatsoever may or can come to pass upon all supposed conditions, yet hath he not decreed anything because he foresaw it as future, or as that which would come to pass upon such conditions."²⁸

This paragraph rejects the doctrine of "middle knowledge" (Latin: scientia media), which teaches that God knows what every free creature would do in any possible set of circumstances, and then bases His decree of election on that foreseen response.²⁹ According to this view, God looks down the corridors of time, sees who will believe, and then chooses them accordingly.³⁰ The confession denies this because it makes God's decree dependent on the creature rather than on His own sovereign will.³¹

The confession cites Romans 9, where Paul repeatedly grounds election in God's own purpose, not in human works or foreseen merit: "though they were not yet born and had done nothing either good or bad—in order that God's purpose of election might continue, not because of works but because of him who calls" (Romans 9:11).³²

The distinction is crucial: God foreknows because He has decreed; He does not decree because He foreknows. Foreknowledge in Scripture is not mere advance awareness but relational, covenantal knowledge—a choosing, loving knowledge (Romans 8:29; 1 Peter 1:2).³³ Peter tells us that believers were chosen "according to the foreknowledge of God the Father," not according to their foreseen faith.³⁴

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 2: Acts 15:18; Romans 9:11, 13, 16, 18.³⁵

