Paragraphs 3–7 – The Specific Decree: Election and Reprobation

Having established the general decree that covers all things, the confession now narrows its focus to the decree of God regarding rational creatures—angels and human beings.³⁶

Paragraph 3 – Double Predestination Stated
"By the decree of God, for the manifestation of his glory, some men and angels are predestinated, or foreordained to eternal life through Jesus Christ, to the praise of his glorious grace; others being left to act in their sin to their just condemnation, to the praise of his glorious justice."³⁷

This is the doctrine of double predestination: God has sovereignly chosen some to salvation (election) and passed over others (reprobation).³⁸ The confession is careful to state the purpose—"for the manifestation of his glory"—and the outcomes: the elect receive grace; the reprobate receive justice.³⁹ The two groups are not symmetrically treated: God actively works grace in the elect, but He merely "leaves" the reprobate to act according to their own sinful natures, which justly condemns them.⁴⁰

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 3: 1 Timothy 5:21; Matthew 25:34; Ephesians 1:5-6; Romans 9:22-23; Jude 4.⁴¹

Paragraph 4 – The Cause of Election: Grace Alone, Not Works
"As God hath appointed the elect unto glory, so he hath, by the eternal and most free purpose of his will, foreordained all the means thereunto."⁴² This paragraph emphasizes that election is unconditional—not based on foreseen faith or good works.⁴³ Those whom God predestined, He also called, justified, and glorified (Romans 8:30). The same decree that appoints the end (salvation) also appoints the means (faith, repentance, perseverance).⁴⁴

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 4: 2 Thessalonians 2:13-14; Ephesians 1:4; John 6:37-39.⁴⁵

Paragraph 5 – The Unconditional Nature of Election
"Those of mankind that are predestinated to life, God, before the foundation of the world was laid, according to his eternal and immutable purpose, and the secret counsel and good pleasure of his will, hath chosen in Christ, unto everlasting glory, out of his mere free grace and love, without any foresight of faith or good works, or perseverance in either of them, or any other thing in the creature, as conditions or causes moving him thereunto."⁴⁶

This is the confession's strongest affirmation of unconditional election. The phrase "without any foresight of faith or good works" directly counters the Arminian claim that God elects based on foreseen belief.⁴⁷ As Louis Berkhof writes, "Election is that eternal act of God whereby He, in sovereign good pleasure, and on account of no foreseen merit in them, chooses a certain number of men to be the recipients of special grace and of eternal salvation."⁴⁸

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 5: Romans 8:28-30; 2 Timothy 1:9; Ephesians 1:5-6, 11.⁴⁹

Paragraph 6 – The Fixed Number of the Elect
The confession affirms that the number of the elect is "so certain and definite, that it cannot be either increased or diminished."⁵⁰ This flows from the immutability of God's decree (Romans 8:28-30; John 10:28-29).⁵¹

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 6: John 10:28-29; 2 Timothy 2:19; Romans 8:28-30.⁵²

Paragraph 7 – Practical Uses of the Doctrine of Predestination
The final paragraph addresses the pastoral purpose of this teaching: "The doctrine of the high mystery of predestination is to be handled with special prudence and care... that men attending the will of God revealed in his Word, and yielding obedience thereunto, may, from the certainty of their effectual vocation, be assured of their eternal election."⁵³

The confession warns against two errors: (1) speculative curiosity that pries into God's secret will, and (2) carnal security that uses election as a license for sin.⁵⁴ Instead, believers are to seek assurance through the means of grace—faith, obedience, and the Spirit's witness.⁵⁵

Key Scripture Proofs for Paragraph 7: Romans 11:33-36; 1 Peter 5:10-11; 2 Peter 1:10-11; Romans 9:20.⁵⁶

