Part 2: Theological Anatomy – The Pillars of a Robust Doctrine of the Decree

The confession's doctrine of the decree rests on several theological pillars, each essential to maintaining biblical orthodoxy.⁵⁷

Pillar 1: The Unity and Simplicity of the Decree

The confession speaks of "the decree" in the singular, not "the decrees." This reflects the theological principle that God's eternal purpose is a single, unified act of His will, encompassing all that comes to pass.⁵⁸ As Berkhof writes, "The decree of God is His eternal purpose, whereby He has foreordained whatsoever comes to pass."⁵⁹ There are not multiple divine plans layered atop one another. The decree is one comprehensive blueprint, though we may distinguish its parts—election, reprobation, creation, providence—for the sake of human understanding.⁶⁰

Pillar 2: The Aseity and Freedom of the Decree

Because God is self-existent (aseity), His decree flows from His own nature, not from any external influence.⁶¹ The confession emphasizes that God decrees "freely"—not because He was compelled by anything outside Himself. As Octavius Winslow observed, "What doctrine is more emptying, humbling, and therefore sanctifying, than predestination? It lays the axe at the root of all human boasting."⁶²

Pillar 3: The Compatibility of Divine Sovereignty and Human Responsibility (Compatibilism)

The confession refuses to resolve the biblical tension between God's sovereign decree and human accountability by denying either pole. Instead, it affirms both, trusting that God has revealed both truths even if human reason cannot fully reconcile them.⁶³ This is compatibilism (not to be confused with philosophical determinism): God's decree and human freedom are compatible because God works through, not against, human choices.⁶⁴ The confession's three "fences" in paragraph 1—denying that God is the author of sin, denying violence to the will, and affirming contingency—establish this compatibilist framework.⁶⁵

Pillar 4: The Unconditional Character of Election

Paragraph 5's affirmation that election is not based on foreseen faith or works is the confession's most explicit declaration of unconditional election.⁶⁶ This does not mean that God's choice is arbitrary or capricious; it means that the ground of election is found in God's own good pleasure, not in any quality or action of the creature.⁶⁷ The Reformed tradition has consistently maintained that God's love for the elect is the cause, not the effect, of their faith.⁶⁸

Pillar 5: The Integration of Ends and Means

The confession refuses to separate the end (salvation) from the means (faith, repentance, perseverance). Paragraph 4 affirms that God "hath, by the eternal and most free purpose of his will, foreordained all the means thereunto."⁶⁹ This guards against antinomianism, which might argue that since God has chosen the elect, their behavior doesn't matter. On the contrary, election ensures the means as surely as it ensures the end. Those whom God predestines, He also calls, justifies, and sanctifies (Romans 8:29-30).⁷⁰

Pillar 6: The Ultimate Purpose: The Glory of God

Chapter 3 repeatedly emphasizes that the decree aims at "the manifestation of his glory" (paragraphs 3, 6, 7).⁷¹ This is the doxological center of the doctrine. God's eternal purpose is not ultimately about human salvation but about the display of His own perfections—His grace in the elect, His justice in the reprobate.⁷² The believer's proper response is not speculation or pride but worship. As John Piper writes, "God's ultimate goal is to display his glory in the highest possible way, and that happens through the manifestation of both his mercy and his justice."⁷³

