Part 3: Pastoral Diagnosis – The Crises of a Diminished or Distorted View of the Decree

The doctrine of God's decree is not a theological luxury for academic specialists. It addresses deep pastoral crises, both in the life of the individual believer and in the health of the local church.⁷⁴

Crisis 1: The Fear That History Is Out of Control

When believers face tragedy, injustice, or suffering, the natural human response is to wonder: "Is anyone in charge? Does anything matter?"⁷⁵ The doctrine of God's decree answers with a resounding yes. Nothing—not the fall of a sparrow, not the rise of a tyrant, not the diagnosis of cancer—falls outside God's eternal purpose.⁷⁶ This is not fatalistic resignation but hopeful trust. As the confession states, in the decree "appears his wisdom in disposing all things, and power and faithfulness in accomplishing his decree."⁷⁷

Crisis 2: The Loss of Assurance

Many believers struggle to know whether they are truly saved. They look to their fluctuating feelings, their imperfect obedience, and their ongoing struggles with sin, and they despair.⁷⁸ The doctrine of unconditional election offers a different ground for assurance: not our grip on God, but God's grip on us.⁷⁹ If election depends on God's sovereign choice before the foundation of the world, then it does not depend on the variable quality of our performance today. Paragraph 7 explicitly states that believers "may, from the certainty of their effectual vocation, be assured of their eternal election."⁸⁰

Crisis 3: The Arrogance of Self-Sufficiency

The human heart naturally gravitates toward self-justification. We want to believe that our salvation is at least partly our own doing—that we chose God, that we believed, that we persevered.⁸¹ The confession's doctrine of unconditional election humbles such pride. As Winslow observed, it "lays the axe at the root of all human boasting."⁸² If we were chosen "without any foresight of faith or good works," then we have nothing to boast in except the Lord (1 Corinthians 1:31).⁸³

Crisis 4: The Antinomian Temptation

The flip side of humility is license. Some might argue, "If God has unconditionally elected me, then my behavior doesn't matter. I can sin freely and still be saved."⁸⁴ The confession anticipates and rejects this error in paragraphs 4 and 7. Because God has ordained the end (salvation), He has also ordained the means (faith, repentance, good works). Those whom God has predestined, He effectually calls, regenerates, justifies, and sanctifies.⁸⁵ Election is not a license to sin; it is a motivation for holiness (Ephesians 1:4).⁸⁶

Crisis 5: The Rejection of God's Justice

Perhaps the most difficult pastoral challenge posed by the doctrine of the decree concerns the fate of the non-elect. Some object that reprobation makes God unjust.⁸⁷ The confession answers by distinguishing between grace (which is unearned favor) and justice (which is receiving what we deserve). If God gave all people what they deserve, all would be condemned. The wonder is not that some are reprobated, but that any are elected.⁸⁸ Paragraph 3 states that the reprobate are "left to act in their sin to their just condemnation, to the praise of his glorious justice."⁸⁹ As Paul asks, "Is there injustice on God's part? By no means!" (Romans 9:14).⁹⁰

