Part 4: Practical Return – Living in Light of God's Eternal Decree

The doctrine of the decree is not a set of propositions to be memorized but a reality to be lived. Here are seven practical steps derived from Chapter 3.⁹¹

Step 1: Handle the Doctrine with Prudence and Care

Paragraph 7 warns that the doctrine of predestination is a "high mystery" to be handled "with special prudence and care."⁹² This means:

Avoid speculative curiosity: Do not waste time trying to peer into God's secret will. Ask instead, "What has God revealed?" (Deuteronomy 29:29).⁹³
Avoid harsh or provocative language: When discussing election with those who disagree, speak with gentleness and respect (1 Peter 3:15).⁹⁴
Avoid using the doctrine to wound others: Election is meant to humble and comfort, not to divide or intimidate.⁹⁵
Step 2: Ground Your Assurance in Effectual Calling, Not Speculation

Paragraph 7 directs believers to attend "the will of God revealed in his Word" and to seek assurance "from the certainty of their effectual vocation."⁹⁶ This means:

Do not try to read your name in the Lamb's Book of Life. Instead, look for the marks of grace in your life: faith in Christ, love for the brethren, a desire for holiness, perseverance in trial.⁹⁷
Use the means of grace: prayer, Word, sacraments, fellowship. These are the channels through which effectual calling comes.⁹⁸
Step 3: Let Election Humble You, Not Puff You Up

If you are a believer, remember that you were chosen "without any foresight of faith or good works." You were not chosen because you were smarter, more spiritual, or more deserving than others. The only difference between you and the most hardened sinner is the sheer, sovereign grace of God.⁹⁹ Let this reality produce:

Gratitude: "Why me?" becomes a daily hymn of praise.
Humility: You have nothing to boast in except Christ.
Compassion for the lost: Since you were saved by grace alone, you cannot look down on those who are not yet saved.¹⁰⁰
Step 4: Trust God's Sovereignty in Times of Suffering

When life falls apart, the doctrine of the decree is not an abstract puzzle but an anchor for the soul. Joseph's words to his brothers become your own: "You meant evil against me, but God meant it for good" (Genesis 50:20).¹⁰¹ Your suffering is not random; it is part of God's eternal purpose for your good and His glory (Romans 8:28).¹⁰² This does not mean suffering is easy, but it means suffering is not meaningless.

Step 5: Reject Fatalism and Embrace Means

God's decree does not mean that your choices don't matter. On the contrary, because God has decreed the end, He has also decreed the means.¹⁰³ If you are elected to salvation, you are elected to faith, repentance, prayer, and obedience. Do not use election as an excuse for passivity. Instead:

Pray: Because God has decreed the end, your prayers are part of His ordained means.
Evangelize: Because God has elected some, the gospel must be preached to all (Romans 10:14-15).¹⁰⁴
Obey: Because God has chosen you for holiness, pursue it with all your might (Ephesians 1:4).
Step 6: Rest in the Immutability of God's Decree

Because God's decree is "unchangeably" fixed, your salvation does not depend on your fluctuating feelings or faltering obedience. If you are in Christ, you are secure. Jesus said, "No one will snatch them out of my hand" (John 10:28).¹⁰⁵ The same eternal decree that chose you before the foundation of the world will preserve you until the day of glory (Romans 8:29-30).¹⁰⁶

Step 7: Preach the Decree Doxologically, Not Polemically

Pastors and teachers must preach predestination as Paul preached it: as a source of praise, not a weapon for division.¹⁰⁷ The confession's paragraphs repeatedly point to doxology: election is "to the praise of his glorious grace" and reprobation is "to the praise of his glorious justice."¹⁰⁸ When the doctrine of the decree is properly understood, it leads not to controversy but to worship. As Paul exclaims, "Oh, the depth of the riches and wisdom and knowledge of God!" (Romans 11:33).¹⁰⁹

