Conclusion: The Deepest Mystery and Sweetest Comfort

Chapter 3 of the 1689 Baptist Confession is not a museum piece of seventeenth-century theology. It is the believer's anchor in a chaotic world. The doctrine of God's decree—His eternal, free, and unchangeable purpose to bring all things to pass for His own glory—is at once the deepest mystery and the sweetest comfort of the Christian faith.¹¹⁰

It is a mystery because we cannot fully reconcile God's sovereignty with human responsibility, nor can we penetrate the secret counsels of the Almighty. Yet it is a comfort because it assures us that history is not spinning out of control, that our salvation does not depend on our fickle wills, and that the same God who chose us before the foundation of the world will keep us to the end.¹¹¹

The confession's concluding paragraph (7) offers wise pastoral counsel: "the doctrine of the high mystery of predestination is to be handled with special prudence and care." It is not for speculative curiosity but for "praise, reverence, and admiration of God." It is not for carnal security but for "humility, diligence, and abundant consolation" to all who sincerely obey the gospel.¹¹²

May we, like the apostle Paul, fall to our knees in worship when we contemplate this great truth: "For from him and through him and to him are all things. To him be glory forever. Amen" (Romans 11:36).¹¹³

A Prayer from Chapter 3 (adapted from the Puritan tradition):

O Lord, who art from everlasting to everlasting: We confess that we have often stumbled at the mystery of Thy decree. We have been tempted to make Thee the author of sin, or to deny Thy sovereignty altogether. Forgive us. Teach us to tremble and to trust—to tremble before Thy holiness, and to trust in Thy goodness.

We thank Thee that Thou hast chosen us in Christ before the foundation of the world, not because of any foreseen merit in us, but out of Thine own mere free grace and love. We thank Thee that our salvation does not depend on our fickle wills but on Thy unchangeable purpose.

Grant us, by Thy Spirit, to handle this high mystery with prudence and care—not for speculation, but for praise; not for pride, but for humility; not for carnal security, but for abundant consolation.

In the name of Jesus Christ, our elect and eternal Redeemer. Amen.¹¹⁴

